FOUR THINGS YOU SHOULD KNOW ABOUT THIS REVIEW OF UNCHARTED 4: A THIEF'S END  BY LUCY O'BRIEN OF IGN

1. 9 out of 10 is still an outstanding score


2. While IGN gave Call of Duty: Advanced Warfare a 9.1 out of 10, that review was by Brian Albert. Lucy O'Brien never personally reviewed a Call of Duty game for IGN. 

3. Lucy O'Brien also said Uncharted 4: A Thief's End  was a remarkable achievement in blockbuster storytelling and graphical beauty, only let down by an overly long third act. 


4. 9 out of 10 is still an outstanding score. Would you verbal attack your teacher or professor if she gave you a 90% on a school test? If you get offended this easily over someone's opinion, I'd hate to imagine how you'd react if your someone stole your wallet. Chill the heck down.

title: Uncharted 4: A Thief's End Review
author: @AwesomeMiles8
comment:
Her criticisms are spot on, and if anything 9/10 is still too high for this game.  This game is a great piece of art, but it's not all that fun to actually play.  Pacing issues, lots of padding throughout, Lots of open, empty areas, and too much brain-dead, boring, repetitive climbing sessions.  Just when the story seems to pick up, it's back to brain-dead climbing on the side of a mountain for 30 minutes, which ruins any sense of story momentum.  They try to add variety to the boring climb by adding stuff like boosting up Sam to drop a crate, or making cinematic jumps that look like Nate may fall, but it's all predictable after the first time you see it.

Previous Drake games, were shorter, yet had much more shootouts, action and balanced it with occasional climbing sessions.   This game is much longer, much less shootouts, much more climbing and walking.  This game should remove 50% of the pointless climbing, padding  and it would've been a much better game, and the story would flow perfectly.

title: Uncharted 4: A Thief's End Review
author: @NyxLunari
comment: I disagree with this review and it actually pisses me off, but to be fair everyone is different and I respect other peoples opinions. My feelings on this game tho is that it is a crown jewel inside a chest filled with stones. You don't get many games like this anymore. Everything lacks imagination these days, and Naughty Dog has always been in the front of the race with their storytelling and creativity. This game was a true masterpiece to me. I played the original UC 1-3 on PS3 and the Nathan Drake collection on PS4, so I would definitely say that I love the games. I absolutely love the characters. Nathan, Elena, and Sully are some of the best and most realistic feeling characters ever made and I compare them to another game (TLOU) which Naughty Dog has also made, in which the characters there are some of the best as well. The witty and funny banter between all the characters always makes me smile. I love hearing their voices, which are excellently acted, they feel like friends, uncles, aunts, whatever you want to call them, but they are very familiar voices and make me smile. The story in UC4 blew me away, and the ending fight had me at the edge of my seat. After the fight and everything was done, the epilogue was so sweet and made me actually feel good and happy. Not many games these days have that effect on people. I just don't personally understand how this game is just a 9. This game is the embodiment of 10/10. It has excellent writing, excellent combat, excellent voice acting, excellent music, and a fantastic cast of characters that grow on you from the first game to the last game, and it was an incredible journey to play all 4 of these works of art.

title: Uncharted 4: A Thief's End Review
author: @Zeemas
comment: I totally agree with the score here. I don't get why people get so butt hurt. There are many moments in the game that are just predictable and cliche that it is just unnecessary. There are quite a few occurrences that aren't needed which doesn't provide any substance or tension in the story. Those moments where Nate slips off rocks isn't putting you on edge. Elena pretending to be dead bit was just stupid which fluctuates the pacing. Those long winded levels were just really repetitive as stated in the review. Cut half of those levels and it wouldn't even make a difference. I wish they spend the time in making those levels with something more different than the norm but I guess they were just trying to hit the 15 hours gameplay mark or something. This means that there isn't much to tell in the story,  so in order to meet the hours they add long winded levels and unnecessary events. I consider The Last Of Us as a much better game because everything you do in the game has meaning to it and the things happening in the game has a reason for it. These are the reasons why, to me, that Uncharted 4 isn't a 10/10 game. This game is the best I've seen in terms of visual quality, with great combat as usual and good acting, but those set backs I mentioned just brings down the whole package a little for me.

title: Uncharted 4: A Thief's End Review
author: @jiojing4136
comment:
I hope this is the last uncharted, although this game was beautifully made I lost interest half way through. Repetitive platforming and box pushing, story was not appealing since its just one location after another, obsessive use of cliffhangers where character "almost" made it, "almost" dropped "almost" died, "almost" slipped, you get the point. No reward system, from beginning to end the same gameplay. 
The only pros about this game was graphics, character interaction of the world, physics and dynamics, voice acting, cutscenes and characters are almost real, dynamic AI.
Cons, bland story, excessive platforming, dry gameplay, lacking of creativity as the author puts it since you will be jumping from ledge to ledge and "almost" fell of the cliff 90% of the time. They should have just made another 'Last of Us' with this kind of graphics, at least you will be inclined to play from beginning to end. I feel like the gameplay and story did not do a good justice compared to the amount of graphical design that was put into.

title: Uncharted 4: A Thief's End Review
author: @XenittX
comment:
They should nuke this comment section.

You should stop comparing ratings of every game with each other, it's an OPINION, by the particular reviewer. What does it matter to you, it's not like they're forcing their opinion on you.. And what's to complaint about a 9 anyway? If I ever had a 9 in class I'd be more than happy, it's a great score for a solid game.

GTA IV got a perfect 10, just like GTA 5, but with your way of thinking, if you didn't like those games, that would mean you will never enjoy a game because no game has ever had a higher rating. 

How can you be so butthurt and triggered, I don't understand. I see this on almost every IGN video, these kids don't understand what an opinion is and how they can be different from their own, so they just freak out and go and insult people. It's interesting to see the stupidity in these comments, and I wonder how these people will ever deal with actual disappointments in the real world.

People are dying in meaningless wars, children are starving of hunger, yet here you are crying out loud because this "stupid and mean reviewer didn't give your favorite fanboy game a 10.

Is there any hope for humanity?

title: Uncharted 4: A Thief's End Review
author: @NrNi9e
comment: Almost finished playing this game. It is amazing in a lot of aspects but agree with the review, third act is way dragged out. I come from playing a lot of tomb raider game and I must say, tomb raider is a bit better than uncharted, the gameplay is just not as smooth. I never feelt the same smooth transition when climbing and shooting stuff as in tomb raider, its hard to explain just have to try both and see for yourself. It is also extremly linear, and non-open world. There is always just one way forward that is it. Which makes it a bit stale. Tomb raider suffers from the same problem, but i still feel more in uncharted like Im basically just travelling along a narrow corridor forwards to something. Would be interesting to see an uncharted, or tomb raider, that takes on a bit of a more open world approach. Like in metal gear solid phantom pain, but with climbing options. Still a fantastic game in many many aspects, i really enjoyed this game (well, except the third act).

title: Uncharted 4: A Thief's End Review
author: @jaym5118
comment: For me, the entire series felt pretty much the same. There wasn't really any major changes to the overall gameplay. And that's both bad and good. Bad because I was never particularly crazy about the gameplay. Good because, at least I knew how to play already with each installment. I hated the fixed camera areas where you can't change the view, or you're forced to run towards the screen. It also annoyed me throughout the series how you can't just freely climb anywhere (like in Assassin's Creed). You have to go through crap just to find a box to stand on in order to reach a ledge. Frustrating!¬† I started playing this series directly after Assassin's Creed Unity and Syndicate. I think the Uncharted games would have been MUCH more fun with the Assassin's Creed gameplay. It was still a great action series. But it definitely had it's flaws. Sadly, it's not the type of games I can picture ever playing again.

title: Uncharted 4: A Thief's End Review
author: @InterEDGE
comment:
Lack of creativity? Well for one thing, the chase sequence is probably the most dynamic and technically impressive action sequence ever in a video game, and the level design is the best in the series. She gave Evil Within a glowing review but that game was janky and uneven as hell. A 9 is still a great score, but some of her complaints are messed up.


I thought the sequence on the island was a bit drawn out too, but they spent the ENTIRE game trying to get to this point, so it makes sense to stay there for a major length of time. It's pacing is also fine, my only complaint being that sense you're on the island, it can all start to look a bit same-y, but thats just because the game was perfect about switching up environments leading up to that point.

title: Uncharted 4: A Thief's End Review
author: @TheBakeryBoy83
comment: Fair & honest review. As great as Uncharted 4 is, it's far from perfect. Imo. I love the encouragement for stealth gameplay (like The Last of Us) but the aiming/shooting mechanics aren't much better than Uncharted 3. Is it so hard to have it smooth like the first two? Platforming controls can be cumbersome as well. They seem to have gotten worse with the third & fourth game. Uncharted 2 will always be best. Best story, controls, villain, characters, set pieces, locations, music, etc. I'd really like to know what the original story for Uncharted 4 was to be, before creator Amy Henning left Naughty Dog. I wonder if it'd been better or worse? Overall, great game & good ending for the characters. Four is a lot like three for me; spectacular moments in a good game that is held back from complete greatness by a few issues, & development choices. Can't help but feel a little disappointed in Uncharted 4. Maybe I was expecting to much, & had my hopes to high.......

title: Uncharted 4: A Thief's End Review
author: @SeanWebcomOfficial
comment:
I can definitely agree with most in saying that this is a very flawed review, but I don't agree with a lot of the reasons that people are using to argue why it's flawed. I know people like to point out how the score they gave for this game doesn't seem to make much sense in comparison to higher scores they give to games that most would consider either inferior, or just as good. But one thing people have to remember, is that IGN isn't just a singular entity. It's comprised of a variety of crew members, who will all have vastly different opinions, perspectives, and biases towards the games are given to review.

Whether certain members are reliable or consistent with their critiques is definitely something that can be argued. But my point is that you can't just simply cherry-pick certain games that IGN as a whole have rated and compare their scores, because they've more than likely been reviewed by completely different people. It's only when the game is reviewed by the same person, that you can properly start to compare and contrast, and judge whether certain critiques consistently line up with one another. There can be exceptions to the rule, but for the most part, it isn't as simple as just comparing random scores.

The main reason why I think this review is flawed, isn't because they didn't give the game a perfect 10. My biggest issue was that a huge chunk of the review was dedicated towards pointing out how drawn out the game's 3rd act was, when it didn't end up having a huge impact on the overall score. Pointing out the issue isn't a problem in it of itself, but when it's given such a huge focus, there has to be a reason for it. The reviewer made it out to be a huge detriment, that took away from the experience in a significant way. But that ended up not being the case, so having it structured in a way that gave the criticism so much attention was pretty much pointless. In the end, it made the overall verdict appear rather confusing, as a lot of what the game did well seemed to be overshadowed by that complaint, but the score didn't reflect that at all. The overall structure of the review was messy and unbalanced, and it lacked consistency and clarity with the points it was trying to make.

That I think was ultimately this review's biggest downfall. Not because they didn't rate the game higher. And I think the people who are just criticizing the review for not giving the game a perfect 10 are being ridiculous. Nothing is immune to criticism, and insinuating that something is ultimately does more harm than good. There are flaws in every piece of media, and acknowledging their flaws, even if it's something you like, isn't a bad thing. Though the weight and/or credibility of certain criticisms can vary from person to person, it's always healthy to keep an open mind about it.

comment: when i started playing the game I thought it was going to be a master piece but after a while of playing I started to feel that i've seen most of what was happening in old uncharted games, also everything was conveniently there for drake for example there was this brown box with wheel every time drake needed to something to help him climb someone would always say let me look for something and five seconds later they would bring that box! and it got me upset that they couldnt atleast changed the color of the box! another thing was the grappling hook was was more like spiderman's web and not an actual grappling hook..you know one that gets stuck and breaks, you always knew you were going to use a the hook when you say that edge sticking out with a rope on it. Also the ending was upsetting for the 4th time he didnt get a treasure, i'm a huge fan of the uncharted series but naughty dog couldve done better, did it deserve a 9/10? no...but it also doesnt deserve a 10/10 because everything was too repetitive and convenient, uncharted 4 had its way of reminding you that this is just a game.

- There are invisible walls you can run into when you try to run around certain corners or around other characters

Best parts for me was:

- Great graphics
- Great acting
- The combat stealth option
- Some amazing climbing sequences
- The smooth controls

Truly, the game must be reviewed as part of a series, because it is not just another entry but a tribute to Nate's former adventures (and other ND games). title: Uncharted 4: A Thief's End Review
author: @chrones56
comment:
Let's look at it this way: Uncharted 4 is unlike it predecessors in the same way that Captain America: Civil War is from the Avengers. Why? Character development. In the previous games, the treasure was the focus of the plot. Civil War was a story focusing on the two main character's flaws than beating up a powerful enemy. 

Both have pacing issues, because it's trying to serve itself two different ways: one side praising the ridiculous fun captured by its predecessors, the other side is trying to explore the characters to make the story more understandable. So there are inevitably places where the product feels sluggish, because it leans on one side a bit too much. You can't really have this cake and eat it, too. 

That being said, it's fair that this reviewer dropped a point on Uncharted 4 for this. However, it was the pre-review thing that wasn't too bright. If you're going to publish a review, publish it once, and make sure it's complete. It doesn't matter if you miss the release date.

title: Uncharted 4: A Thief's End Review
author: @videocrap831
comment:
Everyone shouldn't be annoyed by the score, a 9 is a high score. It's a great score.

What they should be pissed about is this "review in progress" CRAP they keep pulling.

They deliberately do that dishonest crap, so major reviews get more hits and they move more traffic to their site, because people repeat view and check in on the review.

Rarely, it's warranted, sometimes the review er needs to check online features and functionality, sometimes the embargo isn't lifted in time or the publishers send out late review copies.

But most times, it's a way for major websites to quadruple hits. 

It's done deliberately. It's no coincidence that the biggest publications never seem to be able to get their reviews out on time for major releases.

title: Uncharted 4: A Thief's End Review
author: @xSwarzey
comment:
The third act was fine. You spend two thirds of the game frantically racing from one point to another to another, there needed to be a solid breather; considering just how significant the conclusion of the second was, it was actually fitting.

You're labeling a significant portion of the game as repetitive but I guess I'm the only one that felt Rise of the Tomb Raider was just flat out boring; wonder what it was that gave it a better score? Surely nobody is pathetic enough to disregard everything one game does better than another because of the gender of the lead character. Right? Perhaps the somber moments that broke up the repetitiveness of the third act were lost on you; while it slowed, absolutely, it was exploring something almost their entire childhood in the making, or it was the somber moments on the elevators or driving up the rocky path with the rather depressing music drowning out the car noise and the environment. Sure, it wasn't perfect, but it was fine. 

Game deserves better than a 9, better than Rise of the Tomb Raider, better than any Call of Duty released in recent years and absolutely whatever score this next one will get. Truthfully I couldn't give a rat's arse about the score, to me the game was easily the best game I've ever played; 10/10 doesn't cut it. But at least, to reserve some credibility, get better at reviewing games.

title: Uncharted 4: A Thief's End Review
author: @SAGECh33seBurg3ler
comment: A 9 is a solid score hahahaha realistically, a score of 10 should be much harder to achieve given that the game basically needs to be perfect and in reality it's impossible. Only so much work can be done to make it enjoyable, immersive and all that other good stuff without taking so long. Kinks happen but that's just game development, it happens in films (editing mistakes, set workers have a sneaky accidental cameo) and novels (Jane Eyre is a 200+ year old literary masterpiece yet, with its 7th revised edition, there are still grammar and punctuation errors). Not to say that I'm a game developer, because I'm not, but if I were, this is a great score in the grand scheme of things. I want to know what you guys think, what don't you guys seriously like about this review (aside from it being pretty vague but it is also short so it's more concise if anything) or the score this game received? Not to stir the hornets nest but if you have an opinion that can be justified than I'm interested .
